text: I would like to note that even though we all suggested grave hate for <@U6LUSCS1J> the reality is I think in most metas it isn't a problem. Three times a day I see posts from people about cards they're adding to decks that have some big mill component with zero worries it'll bite them. And it's not just randos, it's content creators who I'd think would play in tighter environments. The reality is most metas is probalby just people slamming Craw Wurms into each other.
Here's the problem with any meta. I come from Wichita Falls. Small city, only 100,000 with a respectable EDH crowd. Of the 30ish folks a fair chunk ran graveyard style decks.
I don't mean that in a negative way, really. I'd just wager we think about this in ways 99% of players don't, and it probably results in a little overhtinking when you're talking the average meta.
Run dat hate. Love dat hate.

Now I'm in Dallas, which is much larger in every respect. Oddly I was surprised moving here I thought the community at large would be so different. In reality, they aren't. It's just a larger sample space of roughly the same stats.

Now don't get me wrong. Always hate the yard because in 2018 it's as much of a resource as anything else in the game. But yes, 99% of players in any meta are just doing their thing with little consideration for anything outside of that.
Here in Austin gy hate of some kind is fairly common in the more experienced decks but you also get the randos with Wurms.

Mine is weird in that it's a reflection of me to a degree. Myself and two guys I podcast with basically started it, so there's 30-40 people showing up weekly, but by and large they took their cues on deckbulding from us or took their cues from people who took their cues from us, and we're people who take EDH a bit more seriously than the average person. The meta reflects that, but it's easy to forget that isn't the norm.

Exactly. If you run those odds guess what? A portion of the time it's relevant and the rest of the time not so much. Stats are fine, but it's easy to overbuild when you're trying to cater to the worst case scenario constantly. That's mostly what caused me to become a janky brewer.

<@U4V5EHQ2G> a good chunk of the time that I pod up with sharks I just watch sharks tear at each other while I do my thing. It's not that they don't recognize me as a competent foe, it's just hard to argue something like a yidris storm deck on the verge of critical mass. The relevant threat always demands the answer. I make my living on being on the fringe of that. Even for folks that recognize that, they still choose to go at the obvious threat. I can't blame them, but I also don't agree. That's what's cool about EDH. The politics are as much a strategy as the cards or the plays.
Oh for sure.

I was just mostly making the point that when I'm looking at a deck and thinking what it needs to be competitive with my friends, or Patrick or Henry or whomever, that may not necessarily be applicable to most pods. I look at the faerie deck and think you need x amount of grave hate to combat reanimation, but that probably isn't actually true in most places, and it's hard to think outside that specific bubble.

It wasn't a criticism so much as an observation that it's easy to think of decks in terms of your specific space, but that space might not reflect the edh world at large, particluarly if your space is people who write about edh, etc
Right but what guides your suggestions is good deck building. I don't think it's a criticism at all so much as it is just another perspective.

Think of it like this, most constructed players take their building cues from big builds at pro tour, gp, star city, etc. Those meta are a small percentage of the magic world at large,but they're a concentrated percentage. Even though most are just going to run that build at an FNM they still take their cues from the concentrated niche. I'm no different. I listen to your suggestions and take heed because your perspective is shaped by that in a good way.

At least in the sense that your meta is more a reflection of the concentrated percentage and mine is more reflective of FNM. I appreciate everyone here's input because everyone makes valid and well thought out points from different perspectives. It's awesome.
Having this place to bounce around ideas is fantastic.
yes, well thought out, keep believing that about me, that’s the key to my power
